Incarcerated individuals are five and one-half times more likely to test positive for COVID-19 and three times more likely to die from it than the general public, according to the [University of Chicago Law Review Online](https://lawreviewblog.uchicago.edu/2020/11/16/covid-dolovich/). Among the 1,091 inmates at Stateville, [303 have tested positive](https://www2.illinois.gov/idoc/facilities/Pages/Covid19Response.aspx) for coronavirus and at least thirteen have died. 

In an effort to mitigate prison infection rates, Gov. J.B. Pritzker began [granting clemencies](https://www.chicagotribune.com/coronavirus/ct-coronavirus-pritzker-inmate-commutations-20200409-ql323nt4azfitagdeon5gswn2q-story.html) in March 2020. 

In January, Pritzker announced that corrections workers and inmates would be included along with residents over sixty-five, first responders and education workers in [Phase 1b](https://coronavirus.illinois.gov/s/phase-1b) of the state’s COVID-19 vaccine distribution plan, which began on January 25. The Illinois Department of Corrections [began vaccinating prisoners](https://www.chicagotribune.com/investigations/ct-coronavirus-illinois-prison-vaccine-plan-update-20210213-7pshvlwhmjgopl3qgfxfl46avy-story.html) in mid-February.
